/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/gradient_maker_pool_1777191969/rounds/round_10/merge_stdout.log:1:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Reward accounting mixes deposit amounts with LP shares, enabling reward theft and claim lockups","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:95","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:145","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:168","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:203","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:252","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:292","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:439","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:472","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:505","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:539"],"claim":"Pool rewards accrue per `totalLPShares`, but user reward checkpoints are updated from `mm.tokenAmount + mm.ethAmount` in `provideLiquidity` and `withdrawLiquidity`, while `claimReward` settles against `mm.lpShares`. Once orderbook transfers make `pool.totalLiquidity` diverge from `pool.totalLPShares`, the contract no longer preserves reward invariants for new deposits, withdrawals, or claims.","impact":"If `totalLiquidity` falls below `totalLPShares`, a depositor can mint more LP shares than the basis used for their reward debt and immediately claim rewards that were accrued before they joined. If `totalLiquidity` rises above `totalLPShares`, the opposite mismatch can make `accumulated - rewardDebt` underflow in `claimReward` or the pending-reward calculation in `withdrawLiquidity`, locking users out of rewards and sometimes out of withdrawals.","paths":["Orderbook sends assets out through `transferETHToOrderbook` or `transferTokenToOrderbook`, reducing `pool.totalLiquidity` without reducing `pool.totalLPShares`; the next LP deposits, receives oversized `lpShares`, but their `rewardDebt` is set from deposit amounts instead of shares; an immediate `claimReward` extracts historical fees.","Orderbook sends assets in through `receiveETHFromOrderbook` or `receiveTokenFromOrderbook`, increasing `pool.totalLiquidity` without increasing `pool.totalLPShares`; later `claimReward` or `withdrawLiquidity` computes rewards from a larger deposit-amount basis than the user's share basis, causing arithmetic underflow and reverts."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"LP shares are minted from `tokenAmount + ethAmount`, so inventory shifts can overmint shares and drain the scarcer asset","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:153","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:158","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:160","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:172","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:214","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:216","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:227","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:439","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:472","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:505","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:539"],"claim":"The pool treats liquidity as the raw sum `tokenAmount + ethAmount` and prices LP shares from that sum, even though ERC20 smallest units and wei are not a safe measure of proportional ownership. After orderbook activity changes the pool's token/ETH composition, a new deposit can be credited against the wrong denominator and receive far more LP shares than the deposited assets justify.","impact":"A newcomer can contribute relatively little of the asset the pool actually needs, mint an outsized fraction of LP shares, and then withdraw a disproportionate slice of the pool's more valuable or scarcer inventory. This can directly steal principal from existing LPs and leave the pool insolvent.","paths":["Orderbook trades leave a pool heavily one-sided, but `pool.totalLiquidity` is still tracked as a raw token-plus-ETH sum; an attacker deposits at the accepted ratio, mints shares from `(tokenAmount + msg.value) / pool.totalLiquidity`, and then withdraws a much larger fraction of the scarce side than they funded.","For common 18-decimal tokens, a token-heavy deposit can dominate the raw-sum numerator even when the pool currently has little need for tokens; the minted `lpShares` overstate real contribution and let the attacker exit with excess ETH or tokens from earlier LPs."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"High","confidence":"medium","title":"Deposits use manipulable Uniswap spot reserves instead of the pool's own balances","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:120","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:126","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:132","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:160","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:172","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:576"],"claim":"`provideLiquidity` decides the required token side from the current Uniswap pair reserves returned by `getReserves(token)`, rather than from the pool's own ETH/token balances or a manipulation-resistant oracle. Because the external pair is a spot price, an attacker can temporarily skew the accepted deposit ratio for one block.","impact":"A flash-loan attacker can make the pool accept a deposit composition that is temporarily too favorable, mint LP shares at a mispriced rate, unwind the reserve manipulation, and later withdraw against the pool's real balances. This enables principal extraction from existing LPs whenever the pool's own composition is not perfectly aligned with the manipulated spot ratio.","paths":["Attacker flash-loan trades the Uniswap pair to skew `reserveETH`/`reserveToken`, then calls `provideLiquidity` while the manipulated spot price is live; the contract accepts the distorted ratio and mints LP shares from that mispriced deposit.","If prior orderbook activity already moved the pool away from the external pair's composition, the attacker only needs a small temporary spot move to widen the mismatch further, then can redeem the overminted shares after the flash-loan trade is unwound."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Fee-on-transfer or deflationary tokens are over-credited, creating unbacked LP balances","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:132","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:164","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:172","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:258","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:535","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:539"],"claim":"The contract assumes `safeTransferFrom` delivers the full requested `tokenAmount` and credits both users and pool totals with the requested amount, without checking the actual balance delta after transfer. The same assumption appears when the orderbook returns tokens through `receiveTokenFromOrderbook`.","impact":"With transfer-tax, deflationary, or rebasing-on-transfer tokens, the pool records more tokens than it actually received. That overstates `mm.tokenAmount`, `pool.totalToken`, and `pool.totalLiquidity`, which can overmint LP shares, let early withdrawers take honest users' ETH or tokens, and eventually make withdrawals revert when the contract runs out of real token balance.","paths":["Attacker provides liquidity with a taxed token; the pool books the pre-tax `tokenAmount`, mints LP shares against assets it never received, and the attacker later withdraws a disproportionate share of the honest pool inventory.","Orderbook returns a taxed token through `receiveTokenFromOrderbook`; internal accounting increases by `amount` even though fewer tokens arrived, so later withdrawals or accounting-dependent operations become undercollateralized and can fail."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-006","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Small deposits can mint zero LP shares and become permanently stuck","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:138","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:157","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:160","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:164","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:166","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:209"],"claim":"`provideLiquidity` accepts non-zero ETH and tokens even when `(tokenAmount + msg.value) * pool.totalLPShares / pool.totalLiquidity` rounds down to zero, because there is no `lpSharesToMint > 0` check before user balances and pool totals are updated.","impact":"A depositor can transfer real assets into the pool, receive no LP shares, and then be unable to recover them. `claimReward` requires `mm.lpShares > 0`, while `withdrawLiquidity` later computes `lpSharesToBurn = (mm.lpShares * shares) / 10000` and reverts on `require(lpSharesToBurn > 0)`, so the deposit is effectively donated to existing LPs.","paths":["As the pool share price rises, a victim deposits an amount smaller than one LP-share unit.","`provideLiquidity` transfers the assets and increases `mm.tokenAmount` / `mm.ethAmount`, but `lpSharesToMint` rounds to zero.","Any later attempt to withdraw reverts at `require(lpSharesToBurn > 0)`, and rewards cannot be claimed because the account holds zero LP shares."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-007","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Rebasing or confiscatory tokens can desynchronize accounting and lock LP exits","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:172","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:174","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:213","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:227","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:258","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:468","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:538"],"claim":"Pool state relies on stored counters such as `pool.totalToken` and `pool.totalLiquidity` rather than reconciling against `IERC20(token).balanceOf(address(this))`. If a supported token can reduce balances outside normal transfers, such as a negative rebase, confiscation, or balance burn, the recorded pool inventory diverges from the real token balance.","impact":"Once the contract's actual token balance falls below the stored totals, `withdrawLiquidity` and `transferTokenToOrderbook` can begin reverting when they try to transfer tokens the pool no longer holds, causing partial or total LP lockup. Positive rebases likewise create unaccounted surplus that existing LP accounting cannot redeem.","paths":["A token used by a pool performs a negative rebase or another out-of-band balance reduction against the pool contract.","`pool.totalToken` and `pool.totalLiquidity` remain unchanged because no synchronization occurs.","Later withdrawals or orderbook settlements attempt to move the overstated amount and revert, leaving LP positions stuck until an admin intervenes."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-010","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Existing pools can be bricked or mispriced because pair checks use the current router, not the stored pair","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:53","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:107","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:114","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:120","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:405","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:426","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:495","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:523","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:556","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:576"],"claim":"The contract stores `pools[token].uniswapPair` when a pool is first initialized, but `poolExists()` and `getReserves()` keep resolving pair existence and pricing through the mutable `gradientRegistry.router()` instead of consistently using the stored pair. If the registry/router later points to a different factory or WETH, the live pool state remains tied to the old pair while operational checks start using a new pair or no pair at all.","impact":"A router migration or registry misconfiguration can permanently DOS orderbook transfers and fee distributions for already-live pools, and later deposits can be priced against the wrong market. This can freeze trading/reward flows for existing LPs or misprice new liquidity against unrelated reserves.","paths":["A pool is initialized while the registry points to router A, so `pools[token].uniswapPair` reflects pair A.","Later the owner updates the registry, or the registry updates `router()` to router B with a different factory/WETH or no pair for the token.","`poolExists()` and `getReserves()` now consult pair B while internal balances still belong to the original pool, bricking orderbook/reward operations or mispricing new deposits."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-011","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Reward payouts are not isolated per pool, so one undercollateralized reward bucket can drain unrelated pools","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:90","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:96","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:237","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:243","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:287","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:299"],"claim":"Reward ETH is tracked per pool via `rewardBalance`, but `_updatePool()` only increments that field and neither `claimReward()` nor the full-withdraw reward path check or decrement it. Rewards are therefore paid straight from the contract's shared ETH balance, which also backs every pool's principal.","impact":"If any pool's reward liabilities ever exceed the ETH actually earmarked for that pool, claims from that pool consume ETH belonging to unrelated pools and can cascade a single-pool accounting failure into protocol-wide insolvency or withdrawal DoS. This materially amplifies overcrediting bugs in the reward system.","paths":["A pool becomes reward-undercollateralized, for example because reward accounting overcredits claims or governance drains reward ETH.","A user claims via `claimReward()` or exits fully through `withdrawLiquidity()` on that pool.","Because payouts ignore `pool.rewardBalance`, ETH is sent from the contract's global balance, depleting other pools' backing until unrelated withdrawals or orderbook operations begin reverting."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-014","severity":"Low","confidence":"medium","title":"Reward deposits are stranded when a pool keeps liquidity after total LP shares fall to zero","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:90","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:93","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:158","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:160","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:172","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:278","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:281"],"claim":"`receiveFeeDistribution` accepts ETH whenever `pool.totalLiquidity > 0`, but `_updatePool` immediately returns when `pool.totalLPShares == 0`. If the pool reaches a state with leftover accounted liquidity but no shares outstanding, reward ETH is accepted yet no `accRewardPerShare` update occurs and no participant can ever earn that deposit.","impact":"Reward ETH sent during this zero-share state becomes unallocatable to LPs and effectively disappears from pool economics unless a privileged actor later recovers or repurposes the surplus. This creates a reward sink and can leave reward accounting insolvent versus actual deposits.","paths":["A pool accumulates leftover recorded liquidity while `totalLPShares` eventually drops to zero, for example after a zero-share mint leaves stranded assets that remain after all real LP shares are burned.","The reward distributor calls `receiveFeeDistribution(token)` while `pool.totalLiquidity > 0` and `pool.totalLPShares == 0`.","The ETH is accepted, `_updatePool` returns early, and no current or future LP position has a checkpoint that can claim the deposit."],"round":4,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-015","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Blocking a token freezes the orderbook repayment path while the pool can still accept fresh liquidity","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:60","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:107","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:426","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:460","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:492","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:523"],"claim":"The same `isNotBlocked` modifier gates both outbound transfers to the orderbook and inbound settlement back from the orderbook, but `provideLiquidity` does not check the blocklist at all. If a token is blocked while the orderbook is already holding that pool's assets, the orderbook can no longer return ETH or tokens to the pool, yet users can still add new liquidity to the impaired market.","impact":"A blocklist action taken during an incident can freeze repayment and leave LP funds stranded in the orderbook, turning a temporary operational issue into persistent pool insolvency until governance unblocks the token or performs manual recovery. Because deposits remain open, fresh LP capital can also be socialized into a quarantined or already-undercollateralized pool instead of being stopped by the intended circuit breaker.","paths":["The orderbook withdraws pool inventory through `transferETHToOrderbook` or `transferTokenToOrderbook` as part of a trade or partial settlement.","Before the return leg is completed, governance or the registry marks the token as blocked.","Subsequent repayment through `receiveETHFromOrderbook` or `receiveTokenFromOrderbook` reverts on `isNotBlocked(token)`, leaving the assets outside the pool.","While the token remains blocked, another user can still call `provideLiquidity(token, ...)` and add funds to the same impaired pool even though all orderbook settlement paths remain disabled."],"round":4,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-017","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Orderbook settlement cannot repay assets after draining a pool's tracked liquidity to zero","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:435","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:438","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:467","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:471","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:501","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:532"],"claim":"Both outbound settlement functions decrease `pool.totalLiquidity`, but both inbound settlement functions require `pool.totalLiquidity > 0` before they will accept assets back. If the orderbook ever withdraws the final unit of tracked liquidity from a pool, the contract enters a state where neither `receiveETHFromOrderbook` nor `receiveTokenFromOrderbook` can restore funds.","impact":"A legitimate full-inventory fill or operational mistake can permanently strand pool assets in the orderbook and brick the pool's settlement path until a manual rescue occurs. LP principal can remain outside the pool even if the orderbook is willing and able to repay.","paths":["Prior trades leave a pool one-sided or nearly exhausted on one asset.","The orderbook calls `transferETHToOrderbook` or `transferTokenToOrderbook` for the remaining tracked liquidity, bringing `pool.totalLiquidity` to zero.","When the orderbook tries to return the acquired counter-asset, `receiveETHFromOrderbook` and `receiveTokenFromOrderbook` both revert with `No liquidity`, so the pool cannot be re-capitalized on-chain."],"round":4,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-018","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Owner emergency withdrawals can seize all LP principal and leave pools permanently insolvent","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:317","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:321","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:329","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:348","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:351"],"claim":"`emergencyWithdraw` and `emergencyWithdrawETH` let the owner transfer out the contract's full ETH balance and arbitrary token balances at any time, but they neither pause the system nor decrement `pool.totalEth`, `pool.totalToken`, `pool.totalLiquidity`, `rewardBalance`, or user balances. After the drain, the contract continues operating against stale accounting that still treats the removed assets as present.","impact":"A privileged caller can rug all pool principal and reward funds in a single transaction. LP withdrawals, reward claims, and orderbook settlement can then revert or consume an insolvent shared balance sheet, causing direct theft and permanent lockup for remaining users.","paths":["The owner calls `emergencyWithdrawETH()` and drains all ETH held for principal and rewards; subsequent `claimReward()` or `withdrawLiquidity()` calls revert when the contract can no longer send the owed ETH.","The owner calls `emergencyWithdraw(tokens)` for tracked pool assets; `pools[token].totalToken` and `pool.totalLiquidity` still show inventory, so later withdrawals or orderbook operations fail once the contract tries to transfer tokens it no longer holds."],"round":6,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-019","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"New LPs can dilute and steal outstanding orderbook receivables","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:158","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:160","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:438","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:439","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:471","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:472","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:504","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:505","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:538","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:539"],"claim":"When assets are sent to the orderbook, the contract immediately reduces `pool.totalEth`/`pool.totalToken` and `pool.totalLiquidity`, but it does not track any offsetting receivable for the borrowed inventory. `provideLiquidity` therefore mints new LP shares against a temporarily shrunken denominator, letting new entrants buy into the pool at a discount while earlier LPs still bear the outstanding orderbook exposure.","impact":"A user can wait until the orderbook has pulled most of a pool's inventory, deposit a comparatively small amount, receive an inflated fraction of LP shares, and then capture a pro-rata claim on assets that are later repaid by the orderbook. This dilutes incumbent LPs and can directly transfer recovered principal from earlier LPs to late entrants.","paths":["Existing LPs fund a pool and the orderbook withdraws a large amount through `transferETHToOrderbook` and/or `transferTokenToOrderbook`, depressing `pool.totalLiquidity` while `pool.totalLPShares` stays unchanged.","An attacker provides liquidity during that window; because `lpSharesToMint` is priced from the reduced `pool.totalLiquidity`, the deposit receives more shares than its fair share of the pool's net assets.","The orderbook later repays the borrowed ETH and/or tokens through `receiveETHFromOrderbook` or `receiveTokenFromOrderbook`, restoring inventory that was financed entirely by incumbent LPs.","The attacker withdraws their inflated share balance and exits with a disproportionate slice of the repaid assets."],"round":7,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-020","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Full withdrawals hard-require a successful ETH reward payout, which can trap remaining principal","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:209","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:235","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:243","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:257","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:259"],"claim":"A 100% withdrawal always attempts to send `mm.pendingReward` in ETH before returning principal, and the entire transaction reverts if that reward transfer fails. Users cannot opt to forfeit rewards and withdraw principal only, while partial withdrawals eventually become impossible because `lpSharesToBurn = (mm.lpShares * shares) / 10000` rounds down to zero for the final LP share unless `shares == 10000`.","impact":"If rewards are undercollateralized, or if the LP is a contract/account that rejects plain ETH transfers, the user can be unable to complete their final exit. Depending on the remaining share price, this can permanently lock a meaningful portion of principal along with any accrued rewards.","paths":["A user calls `withdrawLiquidity(token, 10000)` for their final exit.","The function enters the full-withdrawal branch and tries to send `mm.pendingReward` via a raw ETH call before sending back principal.","If that ETH transfer fails, the entire withdrawal reverts and no principal is returned.","Trying to avoid the reward path with a smaller `shares` value eventually leaves a final LP share that cannot be burned because `lpSharesToBurn` rounds to zero, so the user still must rely on the reverting full-withdrawal path."],"round":7,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-021","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"Small fee distributions are permanently stranded because reward dust is never carried forward","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:90","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:95","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:96","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:274","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:281","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:292"],"claim":"`_updatePool` increases `accRewardPerShare` by `floor(ethAmount * SCALE / totalLPShares)` and does not retain the truncated remainder anywhere. `receiveFeeDistribution` still accepts the full ETH amount and `_updatePool` still adds it to `rewardBalance`, but future reward calculations only use `accRewardPerShare`, so any rounded-away remainder is never allocated to LPs.","impact":"Very small fee deposits can accumulate as permanently unclaimable dust inside the contract. The loss per deposit is small, but repeated distributions can strand non-trivial reward value and make realized LP rewards lower than funded rewards.","paths":["The reward distributor sends a small `msg.value` through `receiveFeeDistribution` relative to `pool.totalLPShares`.","`_updatePool` rounds the per-share increment down, potentially all the way to zero, and does not store the leftover remainder for later.","`claimReward` computes rewards solely from `accRewardPerShare`, so the rounded-away ETH is never distributed to any LP."],"round":7,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-023","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Changing the registry or orderbook can strand assets already borrowed by the previous orderbook","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:73","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:75","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:405","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:412","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:492","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:523"],"claim":"Repayment of borrowed ETH and tokens is gated by `onlyOrderbook`, which always checks `gradientRegistry.orderbook()` at call time. If assets are outstanding when the owner swaps to a new registry through `setRegistry()` or the registry rotates its `orderbook()` address, the previous orderbook immediately loses permission to call `receiveETHFromOrderbook` and `receiveTokenFromOrderbook`, even though it may still be holding pool assets.","impact":"A routine upgrade or misconfigured migration can permanently break the repayment path for in-flight inventory held by the old orderbook. Pools can be left undercollateralized even when the previous orderbook is honest and willing to return the borrowed assets, causing LP insolvency or withdrawal failures until an out-of-band rescue occurs.","paths":["The current orderbook borrows pool inventory through `transferETHToOrderbook` or `transferTokenToOrderbook`.","Before that inventory is returned, the owner calls `setRegistry(...)` or the active registry updates `orderbook()` to a new address.","The previous orderbook can no longer satisfy repayment through `receiveETHFromOrderbook` or `receiveTokenFromOrderbook` because `onlyOrderbook` now rejects it, leaving the borrowed assets stranded outside the pool."],"round":8,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-024","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Orderbook loans are not isolated per pool, so repayments can be redirected to a different pool","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:426","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:460","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:492","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:523"],"claim":"The contract never records how much ETH or token inventory the orderbook owes back to each token pool. `transferETHToOrderbook` and `transferTokenToOrderbook` immediately debit whichever pool the orderbook names, while `receiveETHFromOrderbook` and `receiveTokenFromOrderbook` can later credit any other pool the same orderbook chooses, with no check that the repayment matches the pool that originally funded the loan.","impact":"A buggy or compromised orderbook can silently shift principal from one pool to another. LPs in the debited pool are left undercollateralized, while LPs in the credited pool receive an unearned windfall. This breaks pool-level solvency and can socialize losses across unrelated markets.","paths":["The orderbook borrows ETH from pool A with `transferETHToOrderbook(tokenA, amount)` or borrows tokens from pool A with `transferTokenToOrderbook(tokenA, amount)`.","Instead of repaying pool A, it later calls `receiveETHFromOrderbook(tokenB, amount)` or `receiveTokenFromOrderbook(tokenB, amount)` for pool B.","Because no per-pool debt or loan identifier is tracked, the repayment succeeds and pool B is credited while pool A remains short the borrowed inventory."],"round":9,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-103","severity":"High","confidence":"medium","title":"The first depositor after a zero-share state can seize stranded pool assets and later orderbook repayments","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:153","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:155","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:172","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:175","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:501","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:505","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:532","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:539"],"claim":"When `pool.totalLPShares == 0`, `provideLiquidity` always takes the first-provider branch and mints shares equal only to the new contribution, without accounting for any preexisting `pool.totalEth`, `pool.totalToken`, or `pool.totalLiquidity`. Meanwhile, both orderbook repayment functions accept funds whenever `pool.totalLiquidity > 0` even if no LP shares exist. If the pool ever reaches a shareless-but-live state, all leftover inventory and any subsequent repayment become claimable by the next depositor.","impact":"An attacker can wait for a pool to have recorded assets but no outstanding shares, make the next small balanced deposit, receive 100% of the LP shares, and then withdraw all pool ETH and tokens. This can steal principal stranded by earlier accounting bugs and also capture assets that the orderbook later returns.","paths":["A prior accounting edge case leaves `pool.totalLiquidity > 0` while `pool.totalLPShares == 0`, for example after zero-share deposits strand assets and the last real LP shares are burned.","The orderbook may further repay ETH or tokens through `receiveETHFromOrderbook` or `receiveTokenFromOrderbook`, which increase pool balances despite there being no shareholders.","An attacker then calls `provideLiquidity`; because `totalLPShares == 0`, the contract mints shares only from the attacker's deposit and ignores the preexisting assets.","The attacker withdraws 100% of shares and receives all tracked ETH and tokens, including assets that predated the deposit or were later repaid by the orderbook."],"round":5,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Orderbook token transfers trust nominal amounts, so taxed tokens can leak collateral on every fill","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"Partially duplicates F-004, which already captures over-crediting on taxed-token receipts through `receiveTokenFromOrderbook`. The new outbound-leg theory is not a separate supported pool-accounting bug for standard fee-on-transfer tokens because the pool’s own balance usually decreases by the full sent amount."},{"title":"Reward balance is never decremented, permanently overstating pool reward solvency","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"Subsumed by F-011. The stale `rewardBalance` counter is already one mechanism behind the stronger cross-pool reward-drain finding and does not add a distinct protocol-harm path on its own."}]}
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/gradient_maker_pool_1777191969/rounds/round_10/merge_stderr.log:204:    "impact": "A router migration or registry misconfiguration can permanently DOS orderbook transfers and fee distributions for already-live pools, and later deposits can be priced against the wrong market. This can freeze trading/reward flows for existing LPs or misprice new liquidity against unrelated reserves.",
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/gradient_maker_pool_1777191969/rounds/round_10/merge_stderr.log:719:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Reward accounting mixes deposit amounts with LP shares, enabling reward theft and claim lockups","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:95","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:145","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:168","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:203","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:252","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:292","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:439","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:472","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:505","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:539"],"claim":"Pool rewards accrue per `totalLPShares`, but user reward checkpoints are updated from `mm.tokenAmount + mm.ethAmount` in `provideLiquidity` and `withdrawLiquidity`, while `claimReward` settles against `mm.lpShares`. Once orderbook transfers make `pool.totalLiquidity` diverge from `pool.totalLPShares`, the contract no longer preserves reward invariants for new deposits, withdrawals, or claims.","impact":"If `totalLiquidity` falls below `totalLPShares`, a depositor can mint more LP shares than the basis used for their reward debt and immediately claim rewards that were accrued before they joined. If `totalLiquidity` rises above `totalLPShares`, the opposite mismatch can make `accumulated - rewardDebt` underflow in `claimReward` or the pending-reward calculation in `withdrawLiquidity`, locking users out of rewards and sometimes out of withdrawals.","paths":["Orderbook sends assets out through `transferETHToOrderbook` or `transferTokenToOrderbook`, reducing `pool.totalLiquidity` without reducing `pool.totalLPShares`; the next LP deposits, receives oversized `lpShares`, but their `rewardDebt` is set from deposit amounts instead of shares; an immediate `claimReward` extracts historical fees.","Orderbook sends assets in through `receiveETHFromOrderbook` or `receiveTokenFromOrderbook`, increasing `pool.totalLiquidity` without increasing `pool.totalLPShares`; later `claimReward` or `withdrawLiquidity` computes rewards from a larger deposit-amount basis than the user's share basis, causing arithmetic underflow and reverts."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"LP shares are minted from `tokenAmount + ethAmount`, so inventory shifts can overmint shares and drain the scarcer asset","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:153","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:158","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:160","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:172","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:214","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:216","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:227","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:439","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:472","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:505","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:539"],"claim":"The pool treats liquidity as the raw sum `tokenAmount + ethAmount` and prices LP shares from that sum, even though ERC20 smallest units and wei are not a safe measure of proportional ownership. After orderbook activity changes the pool's token/ETH composition, a new deposit can be credited against the wrong denominator and receive far more LP shares than the deposited assets justify.","impact":"A newcomer can contribute relatively little of the asset the pool actually needs, mint an outsized fraction of LP shares, and then withdraw a disproportionate slice of the pool's more valuable or scarcer inventory. This can directly steal principal from existing LPs and leave the pool insolvent.","paths":["Orderbook trades leave a pool heavily one-sided, but `pool.totalLiquidity` is still tracked as a raw token-plus-ETH sum; an attacker deposits at the accepted ratio, mints shares from `(tokenAmount + msg.value) / pool.totalLiquidity`, and then withdraws a much larger fraction of the scarce side than they funded.","For common 18-decimal tokens, a token-heavy deposit can dominate the raw-sum numerator even when the pool currently has little need for tokens; the minted `lpShares` overstate real contribution and let the attacker exit with excess ETH or tokens from earlier LPs."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"High","confidence":"medium","title":"Deposits use manipulable Uniswap spot reserves instead of the pool's own balances","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:120","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:126","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:132","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:160","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:172","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:576"],"claim":"`provideLiquidity` decides the required token side from the current Uniswap pair reserves returned by `getReserves(token)`, rather than from the pool's own ETH/token balances or a manipulation-resistant oracle. Because the external pair is a spot price, an attacker can temporarily skew the accepted deposit ratio for one block.","impact":"A flash-loan attacker can make the pool accept a deposit composition that is temporarily too favorable, mint LP shares at a mispriced rate, unwind the reserve manipulation, and later withdraw against the pool's real balances. This enables principal extraction from existing LPs whenever the pool's own composition is not perfectly aligned with the manipulated spot ratio.","paths":["Attacker flash-loan trades the Uniswap pair to skew `reserveETH`/`reserveToken`, then calls `provideLiquidity` while the manipulated spot price is live; the contract accepts the distorted ratio and mints LP shares from that mispriced deposit.","If prior orderbook activity already moved the pool away from the external pair's composition, the attacker only needs a small temporary spot move to widen the mismatch further, then can redeem the overminted shares after the flash-loan trade is unwound."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Fee-on-transfer or deflationary tokens are over-credited, creating unbacked LP balances","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:132","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:164","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:172","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:258","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:535","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:539"],"claim":"The contract assumes `safeTransferFrom` delivers the full requested `tokenAmount` and credits both users and pool totals with the requested amount, without checking the actual balance delta after transfer. The same assumption appears when the orderbook returns tokens through `receiveTokenFromOrderbook`.","impact":"With transfer-tax, deflationary, or rebasing-on-transfer tokens, the pool records more tokens than it actually received. That overstates `mm.tokenAmount`, `pool.totalToken`, and `pool.totalLiquidity`, which can overmint LP shares, let early withdrawers take honest users' ETH or tokens, and eventually make withdrawals revert when the contract runs out of real token balance.","paths":["Attacker provides liquidity with a taxed token; the pool books the pre-tax `tokenAmount`, mints LP shares against assets it never received, and the attacker later withdraws a disproportionate share of the honest pool inventory.","Orderbook returns a taxed token through `receiveTokenFromOrderbook`; internal accounting increases by `amount` even though fewer tokens arrived, so later withdrawals or accounting-dependent operations become undercollateralized and can fail."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-006","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Small deposits can mint zero LP shares and become permanently stuck","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:138","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:157","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:160","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:164","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:166","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:209"],"claim":"`provideLiquidity` accepts non-zero ETH and tokens even when `(tokenAmount + msg.value) * pool.totalLPShares / pool.totalLiquidity` rounds down to zero, because there is no `lpSharesToMint > 0` check before user balances and pool totals are updated.","impact":"A depositor can transfer real assets into the pool, receive no LP shares, and then be unable to recover them. `claimReward` requires `mm.lpShares > 0`, while `withdrawLiquidity` later computes `lpSharesToBurn = (mm.lpShares * shares) / 10000` and reverts on `require(lpSharesToBurn > 0)`, so the deposit is effectively donated to existing LPs.","paths":["As the pool share price rises, a victim deposits an amount smaller than one LP-share unit.","`provideLiquidity` transfers the assets and increases `mm.tokenAmount` / `mm.ethAmount`, but `lpSharesToMint` rounds to zero.","Any later attempt to withdraw reverts at `require(lpSharesToBurn > 0)`, and rewards cannot be claimed because the account holds zero LP shares."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-007","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Rebasing or confiscatory tokens can desynchronize accounting and lock LP exits","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:172","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:174","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:213","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:227","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:258","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:468","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:538"],"claim":"Pool state relies on stored counters such as `pool.totalToken` and `pool.totalLiquidity` rather than reconciling against `IERC20(token).balanceOf(address(this))`. If a supported token can reduce balances outside normal transfers, such as a negative rebase, confiscation, or balance burn, the recorded pool inventory diverges from the real token balance.","impact":"Once the contract's actual token balance falls below the stored totals, `withdrawLiquidity` and `transferTokenToOrderbook` can begin reverting when they try to transfer tokens the pool no longer holds, causing partial or total LP lockup. Positive rebases likewise create unaccounted surplus that existing LP accounting cannot redeem.","paths":["A token used by a pool performs a negative rebase or another out-of-band balance reduction against the pool contract.","`pool.totalToken` and `pool.totalLiquidity` remain unchanged because no synchronization occurs.","Later withdrawals or orderbook settlements attempt to move the overstated amount and revert, leaving LP positions stuck until an admin intervenes."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-010","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Existing pools can be bricked or mispriced because pair checks use the current router, not the stored pair","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:53","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:107","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:114","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:120","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:405","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:426","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:495","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:523","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:556","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:576"],"claim":"The contract stores `pools[token].uniswapPair` when a pool is first initialized, but `poolExists()` and `getReserves()` keep resolving pair existence and pricing through the mutable `gradientRegistry.router()` instead of consistently using the stored pair. If the registry/router later points to a different factory or WETH, the live pool state remains tied to the old pair while operational checks start using a new pair or no pair at all.","impact":"A router migration or registry misconfiguration can permanently DOS orderbook transfers and fee distributions for already-live pools, and later deposits can be priced against the wrong market. This can freeze trading/reward flows for existing LPs or misprice new liquidity against unrelated reserves.","paths":["A pool is initialized while the registry points to router A, so `pools[token].uniswapPair` reflects pair A.","Later the owner updates the registry, or the registry updates `router()` to router B with a different factory/WETH or no pair for the token.","`poolExists()` and `getReserves()` now consult pair B while internal balances still belong to the original pool, bricking orderbook/reward operations or mispricing new deposits."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-011","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Reward payouts are not isolated per pool, so one undercollateralized reward bucket can drain unrelated pools","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:90","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:96","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:237","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:243","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:287","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:299"],"claim":"Reward ETH is tracked per pool via `rewardBalance`, but `_updatePool()` only increments that field and neither `claimReward()` nor the full-withdraw reward path check or decrement it. Rewards are therefore paid straight from the contract's shared ETH balance, which also backs every pool's principal.","impact":"If any pool's reward liabilities ever exceed the ETH actually earmarked for that pool, claims from that pool consume ETH belonging to unrelated pools and can cascade a single-pool accounting failure into protocol-wide insolvency or withdrawal DoS. This materially amplifies overcrediting bugs in the reward system.","paths":["A pool becomes reward-undercollateralized, for example because reward accounting overcredits claims or governance drains reward ETH.","A user claims via `claimReward()` or exits fully through `withdrawLiquidity()` on that pool.","Because payouts ignore `pool.rewardBalance`, ETH is sent from the contract's global balance, depleting other pools' backing until unrelated withdrawals or orderbook operations begin reverting."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-014","severity":"Low","confidence":"medium","title":"Reward deposits are stranded when a pool keeps liquidity after total LP shares fall to zero","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:90","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:93","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:158","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:160","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:172","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:278","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:281"],"claim":"`receiveFeeDistribution` accepts ETH whenever `pool.totalLiquidity > 0`, but `_updatePool` immediately returns when `pool.totalLPShares == 0`. If the pool reaches a state with leftover accounted liquidity but no shares outstanding, reward ETH is accepted yet no `accRewardPerShare` update occurs and no participant can ever earn that deposit.","impact":"Reward ETH sent during this zero-share state becomes unallocatable to LPs and effectively disappears from pool economics unless a privileged actor later recovers or repurposes the surplus. This creates a reward sink and can leave reward accounting insolvent versus actual deposits.","paths":["A pool accumulates leftover recorded liquidity while `totalLPShares` eventually drops to zero, for example after a zero-share mint leaves stranded assets that remain after all real LP shares are burned.","The reward distributor calls `receiveFeeDistribution(token)` while `pool.totalLiquidity > 0` and `pool.totalLPShares == 0`.","The ETH is accepted, `_updatePool` returns early, and no current or future LP position has a checkpoint that can claim the deposit."],"round":4,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-015","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Blocking a token freezes the orderbook repayment path while the pool can still accept fresh liquidity","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:60","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:107","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:426","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:460","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:492","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:523"],"claim":"The same `isNotBlocked` modifier gates both outbound transfers to the orderbook and inbound settlement back from the orderbook, but `provideLiquidity` does not check the blocklist at all. If a token is blocked while the orderbook is already holding that pool's assets, the orderbook can no longer return ETH or tokens to the pool, yet users can still add new liquidity to the impaired market.","impact":"A blocklist action taken during an incident can freeze repayment and leave LP funds stranded in the orderbook, turning a temporary operational issue into persistent pool insolvency until governance unblocks the token or performs manual recovery. Because deposits remain open, fresh LP capital can also be socialized into a quarantined or already-undercollateralized pool instead of being stopped by the intended circuit breaker.","paths":["The orderbook withdraws pool inventory through `transferETHToOrderbook` or `transferTokenToOrderbook` as part of a trade or partial settlement.","Before the return leg is completed, governance or the registry marks the token as blocked.","Subsequent repayment through `receiveETHFromOrderbook` or `receiveTokenFromOrderbook` reverts on `isNotBlocked(token)`, leaving the assets outside the pool.","While the token remains blocked, another user can still call `provideLiquidity(token, ...)` and add funds to the same impaired pool even though all orderbook settlement paths remain disabled."],"round":4,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-017","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Orderbook settlement cannot repay assets after draining a pool's tracked liquidity to zero","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:435","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:438","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:467","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:471","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:501","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:532"],"claim":"Both outbound settlement functions decrease `pool.totalLiquidity`, but both inbound settlement functions require `pool.totalLiquidity > 0` before they will accept assets back. If the orderbook ever withdraws the final unit of tracked liquidity from a pool, the contract enters a state where neither `receiveETHFromOrderbook` nor `receiveTokenFromOrderbook` can restore funds.","impact":"A legitimate full-inventory fill or operational mistake can permanently strand pool assets in the orderbook and brick the pool's settlement path until a manual rescue occurs. LP principal can remain outside the pool even if the orderbook is willing and able to repay.","paths":["Prior trades leave a pool one-sided or nearly exhausted on one asset.","The orderbook calls `transferETHToOrderbook` or `transferTokenToOrderbook` for the remaining tracked liquidity, bringing `pool.totalLiquidity` to zero.","When the orderbook tries to return the acquired counter-asset, `receiveETHFromOrderbook` and `receiveTokenFromOrderbook` both revert with `No liquidity`, so the pool cannot be re-capitalized on-chain."],"round":4,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-018","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Owner emergency withdrawals can seize all LP principal and leave pools permanently insolvent","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:317","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:321","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:329","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:348","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:351"],"claim":"`emergencyWithdraw` and `emergencyWithdrawETH` let the owner transfer out the contract's full ETH balance and arbitrary token balances at any time, but they neither pause the system nor decrement `pool.totalEth`, `pool.totalToken`, `pool.totalLiquidity`, `rewardBalance`, or user balances. After the drain, the contract continues operating against stale accounting that still treats the removed assets as present.","impact":"A privileged caller can rug all pool principal and reward funds in a single transaction. LP withdrawals, reward claims, and orderbook settlement can then revert or consume an insolvent shared balance sheet, causing direct theft and permanent lockup for remaining users.","paths":["The owner calls `emergencyWithdrawETH()` and drains all ETH held for principal and rewards; subsequent `claimReward()` or `withdrawLiquidity()` calls revert when the contract can no longer send the owed ETH.","The owner calls `emergencyWithdraw(tokens)` for tracked pool assets; `pools[token].totalToken` and `pool.totalLiquidity` still show inventory, so later withdrawals or orderbook operations fail once the contract tries to transfer tokens it no longer holds."],"round":6,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-019","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"New LPs can dilute and steal outstanding orderbook receivables","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:158","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:160","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:438","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:439","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:471","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:472","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:504","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:505","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:538","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:539"],"claim":"When assets are sent to the orderbook, the contract immediately reduces `pool.totalEth`/`pool.totalToken` and `pool.totalLiquidity`, but it does not track any offsetting receivable for the borrowed inventory. `provideLiquidity` therefore mints new LP shares against a temporarily shrunken denominator, letting new entrants buy into the pool at a discount while earlier LPs still bear the outstanding orderbook exposure.","impact":"A user can wait until the orderbook has pulled most of a pool's inventory, deposit a comparatively small amount, receive an inflated fraction of LP shares, and then capture a pro-rata claim on assets that are later repaid by the orderbook. This dilutes incumbent LPs and can directly transfer recovered principal from earlier LPs to late entrants.","paths":["Existing LPs fund a pool and the orderbook withdraws a large amount through `transferETHToOrderbook` and/or `transferTokenToOrderbook`, depressing `pool.totalLiquidity` while `pool.totalLPShares` stays unchanged.","An attacker provides liquidity during that window; because `lpSharesToMint` is priced from the reduced `pool.totalLiquidity`, the deposit receives more shares than its fair share of the pool's net assets.","The orderbook later repays the borrowed ETH and/or tokens through `receiveETHFromOrderbook` or `receiveTokenFromOrderbook`, restoring inventory that was financed entirely by incumbent LPs.","The attacker withdraws their inflated share balance and exits with a disproportionate slice of the repaid assets."],"round":7,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-020","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Full withdrawals hard-require a successful ETH reward payout, which can trap remaining principal","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:209","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:235","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:243","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:257","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:259"],"claim":"A 100% withdrawal always attempts to send `mm.pendingReward` in ETH before returning principal, and the entire transaction reverts if that reward transfer fails. Users cannot opt to forfeit rewards and withdraw principal only, while partial withdrawals eventually become impossible because `lpSharesToBurn = (mm.lpShares * shares) / 10000` rounds down to zero for the final LP share unless `shares == 10000`.","impact":"If rewards are undercollateralized, or if the LP is a contract/account that rejects plain ETH transfers, the user can be unable to complete their final exit. Depending on the remaining share price, this can permanently lock a meaningful portion of principal along with any accrued rewards.","paths":["A user calls `withdrawLiquidity(token, 10000)` for their final exit.","The function enters the full-withdrawal branch and tries to send `mm.pendingReward` via a raw ETH call before sending back principal.","If that ETH transfer fails, the entire withdrawal reverts and no principal is returned.","Trying to avoid the reward path with a smaller `shares` value eventually leaves a final LP share that cannot be burned because `lpSharesToBurn` rounds to zero, so the user still must rely on the reverting full-withdrawal path."],"round":7,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-021","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"Small fee distributions are permanently stranded because reward dust is never carried forward","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:90","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:95","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:96","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:274","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:281","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:292"],"claim":"`_updatePool` increases `accRewardPerShare` by `floor(ethAmount * SCALE / totalLPShares)` and does not retain the truncated remainder anywhere. `receiveFeeDistribution` still accepts the full ETH amount and `_updatePool` still adds it to `rewardBalance`, but future reward calculations only use `accRewardPerShare`, so any rounded-away remainder is never allocated to LPs.","impact":"Very small fee deposits can accumulate as permanently unclaimable dust inside the contract. The loss per deposit is small, but repeated distributions can strand non-trivial reward value and make realized LP rewards lower than funded rewards.","paths":["The reward distributor sends a small `msg.value` through `receiveFeeDistribution` relative to `pool.totalLPShares`.","`_updatePool` rounds the per-share increment down, potentially all the way to zero, and does not store the leftover remainder for later.","`claimReward` computes rewards solely from `accRewardPerShare`, so the rounded-away ETH is never distributed to any LP."],"round":7,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-023","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Changing the registry or orderbook can strand assets already borrowed by the previous orderbook","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:73","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:75","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:405","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:412","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:492","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:523"],"claim":"Repayment of borrowed ETH and tokens is gated by `onlyOrderbook`, which always checks `gradientRegistry.orderbook()` at call time. If assets are outstanding when the owner swaps to a new registry through `setRegistry()` or the registry rotates its `orderbook()` address, the previous orderbook immediately loses permission to call `receiveETHFromOrderbook` and `receiveTokenFromOrderbook`, even though it may still be holding pool assets.","impact":"A routine upgrade or misconfigured migration can permanently break the repayment path for in-flight inventory held by the old orderbook. Pools can be left undercollateralized even when the previous orderbook is honest and willing to return the borrowed assets, causing LP insolvency or withdrawal failures until an out-of-band rescue occurs.","paths":["The current orderbook borrows pool inventory through `transferETHToOrderbook` or `transferTokenToOrderbook`.","Before that inventory is returned, the owner calls `setRegistry(...)` or the active registry updates `orderbook()` to a new address.","The previous orderbook can no longer satisfy repayment through `receiveETHFromOrderbook` or `receiveTokenFromOrderbook` because `onlyOrderbook` now rejects it, leaving the borrowed assets stranded outside the pool."],"round":8,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-024","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Orderbook loans are not isolated per pool, so repayments can be redirected to a different pool","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:426","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:460","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:492","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:523"],"claim":"The contract never records how much ETH or token inventory the orderbook owes back to each token pool. `transferETHToOrderbook` and `transferTokenToOrderbook` immediately debit whichever pool the orderbook names, while `receiveETHFromOrderbook` and `receiveTokenFromOrderbook` can later credit any other pool the same orderbook chooses, with no check that the repayment matches the pool that originally funded the loan.","impact":"A buggy or compromised orderbook can silently shift principal from one pool to another. LPs in the debited pool are left undercollateralized, while LPs in the credited pool receive an unearned windfall. This breaks pool-level solvency and can socialize losses across unrelated markets.","paths":["The orderbook borrows ETH from pool A with `transferETHToOrderbook(tokenA, amount)` or borrows tokens from pool A with `transferTokenToOrderbook(tokenA, amount)`.","Instead of repaying pool A, it later calls `receiveETHFromOrderbook(tokenB, amount)` or `receiveTokenFromOrderbook(tokenB, amount)` for pool B.","Because no per-pool debt or loan identifier is tracked, the repayment succeeds and pool B is credited while pool A remains short the borrowed inventory."],"round":9,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-103","severity":"High","confidence":"medium","title":"The first depositor after a zero-share state can seize stranded pool assets and later orderbook repayments","locations":["contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:153","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:155","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:172","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:175","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:501","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:505","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:532","contracts/GradientMarketMakerPool.sol:539"],"claim":"When `pool.totalLPShares == 0`, `provideLiquidity` always takes the first-provider branch and mints shares equal only to the new contribution, without accounting for any preexisting `pool.totalEth`, `pool.totalToken`, or `pool.totalLiquidity`. Meanwhile, both orderbook repayment functions accept funds whenever `pool.totalLiquidity > 0` even if no LP shares exist. If the pool ever reaches a shareless-but-live state, all leftover inventory and any subsequent repayment become claimable by the next depositor.","impact":"An attacker can wait for a pool to have recorded assets but no outstanding shares, make the next small balanced deposit, receive 100% of the LP shares, and then withdraw all pool ETH and tokens. This can steal principal stranded by earlier accounting bugs and also capture assets that the orderbook later returns.","paths":["A prior accounting edge case leaves `pool.totalLiquidity > 0` while `pool.totalLPShares == 0`, for example after zero-share deposits strand assets and the last real LP shares are burned.","The orderbook may further repay ETH or tokens through `receiveETHFromOrderbook` or `receiveTokenFromOrderbook`, which increase pool balances despite there being no shareholders.","An attacker then calls `provideLiquidity`; because `totalLPShares == 0`, the contract mints shares only from the attacker's deposit and ignores the preexisting assets.","The attacker withdraws 100% of shares and receives all tracked ETH and tokens, including assets that predated the deposit or were later repaid by the orderbook."],"round":5,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Orderbook token transfers trust nominal amounts, so taxed tokens can leak collateral on every fill","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"Partially duplicates F-004, which already captures over-crediting on taxed-token receipts through `receiveTokenFromOrderbook`. The new outbound-leg theory is not a separate supported pool-accounting bug for standard fee-on-transfer tokens because the pool’s own balance usually decreases by the full sent amount."},{"title":"Reward balance is never decremented, permanently overstating pool reward solvency","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"Subsumed by F-011. The stale `rewardBalance` counter is already one mechanism behind the stronger cross-pool reward-drain finding and does not add a distinct protocol-harm path on its own."}]}
