 to treat the user as staked.","impact":"Users can pull out principal and still retain reward or voting weight in the staking snapshots, leading to reward theft, denominator distortion, and persistent accounting corruption for the pool. Because the gate is based on global token inactivity, this is reachable during ordinary operation for quiet pools, not only during genuine emergencies.","paths":["User stakes a non-stable token and accumulates normal checkpoints.","If that token has not had a successful withdrawal for 10 epochs, the user calls `emergencyWithdraw(token)` and receives their full principal.","Subsequent `getEpochUserBalance(user, token, epoch)` calls still return the stale checkpointed balance, and later pool snapshots can inherit the stale size."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Historical pool sizes are retroactively mutable for uninitialized epochs","locations":["Staking.sol:466","Staking.sol:558","Staking.sol:572","Staking.sol:579"],"claim":"`getEpochPoolSize` is documented as returning the amount locked during a specific epoch, but if that epoch was never initialized it falls back to the contract's current token holdings (`stableCoinBalances` for stablecoins or `token.balanceOf(address(this))` for other tokens). As a result, skipped epochs do not have immutable historical values and can report whatever the contract balance is at query time.","impact":"Any reward or accounting logic that queries past epochs without first forcing sequential initialization can read a rewritten denominator instead of the real pool size that existed in that epoch. This can misprice rewards and historical stake calculations for idle periods.","paths":["Epoch `N` passes without anyone initializing that token's pool size for the epoch.","Later deposits, withdrawals, emergency withdrawals, or direct token transfers change the contract's present balance.","A call to `getEpochPoolSize(token, N)` now returns the new balance rather than the true epoch-`N` pool size."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Arbitrary-token deposits credit the requested amount even when fewer or no tokens are received","locations":["Staking.sol:117","Staking.sol:125","Staking.sol:129","Staking.sol:136"],"claim":"For non-stable assets, `deposit` accepts any `tokenAddress`, performs a raw `transferFrom`, ignores its boolean return value, and then credits `balances[msg.sender][tokenAddress] += amount` plus checkpoint state using the user-supplied `amount`. The code never measures the actual amount received, so fee-on-transfer tokens and malicious ERC-20s that under-deliver or simply return `false` can mint unbacked stake.","impact":"Attackers can create undercollateralized positions, farm rewards with less capital than recorded, and potentially withdraw honest users' later deposits of the same token. The pool's internal stake accounting can exceed the assets actually held by the contract.","paths":["Attacker chooses a non-stable ERC-20 that charges transfer fees or maliciously returns `false`/under-delivers.","`deposit` records the full requested `amount` as stake even though the contract receives less or nothing.","The attacker later uses the inflated balance for rewards or withdraws against liquidity supplied by honest users of the same token."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-005","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Ignored Compound error codes can leave stablecoin accounting in a silently failed state","locations":["Staking.sol:259","Staking.sol:262","Staking.sol:265","Staking.sol:321","Staking.sol:340"],"claim":"Compound's `mint`, `redeem`, and `redeemUnderlying` return numeric error codes, but this contract ignores those values everywhere. Stablecoin deposits update internal balances before proving that `mint` succeeded, and withdrawals/interests paths assume redemptions succeeded as long as the call itself did not revert.","impact":"If Compound returns a non-zero error code, the transaction can still succeed while the protocol's assumptions about where funds reside are wrong. A failed `mint` can leave stablecoins sitting idle in the contract while the pool believes the Compound step succeeded, and failed redemptions can cause temporary withdrawal DoS or cause unrelated idle funds to be used to satisfy withdrawals. This also creates a risk that a failed `mint` leaves a non-zero cToken allowance behind, causing later `safeApprove` calls for that stablecoin to revert and freezing new deposits.","paths":["A stablecoin deposit transfers tokens into the contract and increments `stableCoinBalances`, then calls `CTokenInterface(cToken).mint(amount)`.","Compound returns a non-zero error code instead of reverting, but the staking transaction still succeeds because the return value is ignored.","The pool continues in a partially failed state: assets may remain idle, later redemptions can misbehave, and future deposits can be blocked if the stale allowance is still non-zero."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-006","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Skipped epochs and the hardcoded 2021 epoch start can brick dormant or never-before-used pools","locations":["Staking.sol:90","Staking.sol:91","Staking.sol:142","Staking.sol:145","Staking.sol:387","Staking.sol:466","Staking.sol:477"],"claim":"The constructor permanently hardcodes `epoch1Start = 1624230000` (June 21, 2021), while `deposit` and `withdraw` only attempt to initialize the current epoch. `manualEpochInit` then reverts unless `epochId - 1` is already initialized. Once `currentEpoch` has advanced beyond a pool's last initialized epoch—either because a pool sat idle for several epochs or because a token pool is first used long after June 2021—the next `deposit` or `withdraw` hits `manualEpochInit(..., currentEpoch)` and reverts until every missing epoch is backfilled sequentially.","impact":"Dormant pools lose liveness, and fresh deployments, migrations, or late-added token pools can start effectively unusable. Users may face practical lockup until someone spends one transaction per missing epoch to restore the pool's initialization chain.","paths":["The contract is deployed after June 21, 2021, or a token is first used only after many epochs have already elapsed.","A user's first `deposit(token, amount, referrer)` or later `withdraw(token, amount)` calls `manualEpochInit(token, currentEpoch)`.","`manualEpochInit` requires `epochId - 1` to already be initialized and reverts because the skipped epochs were never backfilled.","The pool cannot be used again until someone initializes every missing epoch one by one."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-007","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Stablecoin stakers have no on-contract fallback exit if the Compound integration becomes unavailable","locations":["Staking.sol:119","Staking.sol:127","Staking.sol:370","Staking.sol:489"],"claim":"Stablecoin deposits are automatically forwarded into Compound, while `emergencyWithdraw` explicitly rejects stablecoins. That leaves `withdraw` as the only principal exit path for USDC/USDT/DAI, and it depends entirely on successful Compound redemption.","impact":"If the Compound market is paused, lacks cash, or otherwise becomes unusable for redemption, stablecoin stakers can be left without any protocol-level escape hatch for principal. This turns an external integration failure into a full lockup for those pools.","paths":["A user deposits USDC, USDT, or DAI, and the contract forwards the funds into the corresponding cToken market.","Compound later cannot redeem the requested underlying, whether because liquidity is unavailable or the market integration is broken.","The user's `withdraw` cannot source principal from anywhere else, and `emergencyWithdraw` is unavailable because stablecoins are hard-blocked."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-008","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Withdraw and emergency-withdraw can silently burn a user's claim when token transfers return false","locations":["Staking.sol:368","Staking.sol:374","Staking.sol:376","Staking.sol:379","Staking.sol:495","Staking.sol:498"],"claim":"Outgoing token transfers in `withdraw` and `emergencyWithdraw` ignore the ERC-20 return value on every standard-ERC20 path. The functions reduce or erase the user's recorded balance before calling `transfer`, so a token that returns `false` instead of reverting causes the transaction to succeed without paying the user.","impact":"Users can lose some or all of their staking position while receiving no tokens back. Because arbitrary non-stable ERC-20s are accepted, a faulty or malicious token can permanently desynchronize the protocol's accounting from actual payouts and trap value in the contract.","paths":["A user stakes a token whose `transfer` returns `false` on outbound payouts.","The user calls `withdraw` or `emergencyWithdraw`, which first decrements or zeroes `balances[msg.sender][token]`.","The token transfer returns `false`, but the contract does not check it and does not revert.","The transaction succeeds while the user receives no tokens and their claim has already been reduced or erased."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-010","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Non-stable pool snapshots trust raw contract balances instead of tracked user stake","locations":["Staking.sol:149","Staking.sol:153","Staking.sol:394","Staking.sol:398","Staking.sol:558","Staking.sol:579"],"claim":"For non-stable assets, both `deposit` and `withdraw` set `poolSize[token][currentEpoch + 1]` from `IERC20(token).balanceOf(address(this))`, and `getEpochPoolSize` also falls back to that raw balance for uninitialized epochs. Because pool sizing is derived from the token's live contract balance instead of the sum of tracked user balances, unsolicited transfers, rebases, reflection mechanics, or a malicious `balanceOf` implementation can change pool sizes without changing `balances` or user checkpoints.","impact":"Epoch denominators can diverge from the actual staked positions the contract tracks, distorting any reward or accounting logic that relies on pool size. Negative balance drift can also leave the contract undercollateralized relative to recorded user claims, while inflated balances can dilute or manipulate rewards.","paths":["An attacker or the token itself changes the staking contract's token balance without going through `deposit` or `withdraw`.","A later interaction stores that raw balance into `poolSize[token][currentEpoch + 1]`, or `getEpochPoolSize` returns the raw balance for an uninitialized epoch.","Pool-size snapshots no longer match the recorded user stakes, corrupting downstream accounting."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-011","severity":"Medium","confidence":"low","title":"Permissionless interest sweeps can front-run stablecoin withdrawals and worsen liquidity shortfalls","locations":["Staking.sol:306","Staking.sol:321","Staking.sol:332","Staking.sol:340","Staking.sol:363","Staking.sol:372"],"claim":"`getInterestFromCompound` and `getInterest` are permissionless even though the latter is only commented as being recommended after users have exited. Any third party can redeem accrued underlying from Compound and forward the extracted amount to `TEAM_ADDRESS` before users withdraw. When Compound cash is tight, this can consume redeemable liquidity that would otherwise remain available for user withdrawals.","impact":"An outsider can grief stablecoin stakers by making borderline-liquid pools fail withdrawals sooner or remain illiquid longer, amplifying the contract's existing lack of any fallback exit for stablecoin positions.","paths":["Compound has only limited spare cash above the pool's tracked principal.","A third party front-runs a user's stablecoin withdrawal with `getInterestFromCompound(token)` or `getInterest(token)`.","The contract redeems underlying and forwards the extracted amount to `TEAM_ADDRESS`.","The user's later `withdraw` faces a smaller redeemable buffer and can no longer redeem cleanly from Compound."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Fee-on-transfer withdrawals burn the full stake even when the user receives less","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"Rejected as a separate issue because the claimed shortfall comes from the token's own outbound transfer tax/burn semantics, while the contract balance also decreases by the full nominal amount. The material protocol-specific unsupported-token problems are already covered by F-004 and F-008."}]}
