full claim even when outbound tokens fail or short-pay","locations":["Staking.sol:368","Staking.sol:374","Staking.sol:376","Staking.sol:379","Staking.sol:495","Staking.sol:498"],"claim":"Exit paths debit the user's recorded stake by the requested `amount` before attempting the token transfer, but they never validate the actual payout. If a token returns `false` instead of reverting, the transaction can succeed without paying the user at all; if a fee-on-transfer, deflationary, or malicious token returns `true` while transferring less than requested, the user is still debited for the full amount. `emergencyWithdraw()` has the same flaw for arbitrary non-stable tokens because it zeroes the recorded balance before transferring the entire principal.","impact":"Users can permanently lose some or all of their principal on exit while the protocol treats their claim as fully satisfied. Because arbitrary non-stable ERC-20s are accepted, a faulty or malicious token can desynchronize accounting from real payouts and trap or skim value from stakers.","paths":["A user stakes a token whose outbound `transfer` either returns `false` or transfers less than the requested amount while still returning success.","The user calls `withdraw()` or `emergencyWithdraw()`, which first decrements or zeroes the recorded balance.","The outbound transfer underpays or pays nothing, but the contract does not revert or restore the user's claim.","The transaction succeeds while the user's remaining on-contract claim has already been reduced or erased."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-010","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Non-stable pool snapshots trust raw contract balances instead of tracked user stake","locations":["Staking.sol:149","Staking.sol:153","Staking.sol:394","Staking.sol:398","Staking.sol:558","Staking.sol:579"],"claim":"For non-stable assets, both `deposit` and `withdraw` set `poolSize[token][currentEpoch + 1]` from `IERC20(token).balanceOf(address(this))`, and `getEpochPoolSize` also falls back to that raw balance for uninitialized epochs. Because pool sizing is derived from the token's live contract balance instead of the sum of tracked user balances, unsolicited transfers, rebases, reflection mechanics, or a malicious `balanceOf` implementation can change pool sizes without changing `balances` or user checkpoints.","impact":"Epoch denominators can diverge from the actual staked positions the contract tracks, distorting any reward or accounting logic that relies on pool size. Negative balance drift can also leave the contract undercollateralized relative to recorded user claims, while inflated balances can dilute or manipulate rewards.","paths":["An attacker or the token itself changes the staking contract's token balance without going through `deposit` or `withdraw`.","A later interaction stores that raw balance into `poolSize[token][currentEpoch + 1]`, or `getEpochPoolSize` returns the raw balance for an uninitialized epoch.","Pool-size snapshots no longer match the recorded user stakes, corrupting downstream accounting."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-011","severity":"Medium","confidence":"low","title":"Permissionless interest sweeps can front-run stablecoin withdrawals and worsen liquidity shortfalls","locations":["Staking.sol:306","Staking.sol:321","Staking.sol:332","Staking.sol:340","Staking.sol:363","Staking.sol:372"],"claim":"`getInterestFromCompound` and `getInterest` are permissionless even though the latter is only commented as being recommended after users have exited. Any third party can redeem accrued underlying from Compound and forward the extracted amount to `TEAM_ADDRESS` before users withdraw. When Compound cash is tight, this can consume redeemable liquidity that would otherwise remain available for user withdrawals.","impact":"An outsider can grief stablecoin stakers by making borderline-liquid pools fail withdrawals sooner or remain illiquid longer, amplifying the contract's existing lack of any fallback exit for stablecoin positions.","paths":["Compound has only limited spare cash above the pool's tracked principal.","A third party front-runs a user's stablecoin withdrawal with `getInterestFromCompound(token)` or `getInterest(token)`.","The contract redeems underlying and forwards the extracted amount to `TEAM_ADDRESS`.","The user's later `withdraw` faces a smaller redeemable buffer and can no longer redeem cleanly from Compound."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-012","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Anyone can overwrite an already-initialized epoch-0 pool snapshot","locations":["Staking.sol:466","Staking.sol:472","Staking.sol:479"],"claim":"`manualEpochInit()` special-cases `epochId == 0` by unconditionally writing `poolSize[token][0] = 0` and `set = true`, without checking whether epoch 0 was already initialized with a real nonzero size. Any caller can therefore reset an existing epoch-0 snapshot after pre-start deposits have populated it.","impact":"Pre-start stakers can be erased from the baseline pool accounting used to seed later epochs. If epoch 1 and subsequent epochs are still initialized lazily, an attacker can propagate the forged zero snapshot forward and distort or deny the initial reward allocation for legitimate stakers.","paths":["Users deposit before epoch 1 starts, so epoch 0 is initialized and `poolSize[token][0]` becomes nonzero.","An attacker later calls `manualEpochInit([token], 0)`, which overwrites that existing snapshot with zero.","Before any real interaction repairs the chain, the attacker or anyone else initializes later epochs from the forged predecessor, propagating the zero baseline into live reward epochs."],"round":5,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-013","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Permissionless `getInterest()` can confiscate unrelated stablecoins held by the contract","locations":["Staking.sol:332","Staking.sol:340","Staking.sol:342","Staking.sol:344","Staking.sol:349"],"claim":"`getInterest()` redeems all cTokens for a stablecoin and then treats every on-contract token balance above `stableCoinBalances[token]` as team-owned interest. The function does not distinguish real Compound yield from unrelated stablecoins already sitting on the contract, such as accidental direct transfers or principal stranded on the contract by earlier accounting mismatches, as long as some cToken balance exists to satisfy the function's entry check.","impact":"Stablecoins that do not belong to the team can be irreversibly transferred to `TEAM_ADDRESS` by any caller. This turns stray transfers or previously stranded principal into permanent loss of funds for their rightful owner.","paths":["Stablecoins end up on the staking contract without increasing `stableCoinBalances[token]`, while the contract still holds some corresponding cTokens.","Any account calls `getInterest(token)`, which redeems all cTokens for that market.","The function computes `interest = IERC20(token).balanceOf(address(this)) - stableCoinBalances[token]` and transfers that full difference to `TEAM_ADDRESS`, including unrelated funds."],"round":5,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-014","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Unexpected cToken transfers are misclassified as protocol yield and can be swept to the team","locations":["Staking.sol:286","Staking.sol:314","Staking.sol:318","Staking.sol:336","Staking.sol:344"],"claim":"The interest-handling logic treats the contract's entire Compound position as if it were backed by tracked user principal. If anyone transfers `cUSDC`, `cUSDT`, or `cDAI` directly to the staking contract, `balanceOfUnderlying(address(this))` and later redeemed underlying increase while `stableCoinBalances[token]` does not, so the surplus is classified as withdrawable 'interest' and can be redeemed and forwarded to `TEAM_ADDRESS`.","impact":"Accidentally or intentionally transferred cTokens are confiscatable. Any caller can trigger `getInterestFromCompound()` to redeem most of their underlying value to the team, and `getInterest()` can ultimately sweep the remainder as well. This broadens the asset-confiscation surface beyond raw stablecoins already sitting in the contract wallet.","paths":["A third party transfers `cUSDC`, `cUSDT`, or `cDAI` directly to the staking contract.","`stableCoinBalances[token]` stays unchanged, but the contract's Compound position and its underlying value rise.","Any caller invokes `getInterestFromCompound(token)` or `getInterest(token)`.","The donated cToken position is treated as excess yield and its underlying is sent to `TEAM_ADDRESS`."],"round":6,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-015","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Withdrawal checkpoint math lets users keep late deposits with inflated same-epoch weight","locations":["Staking.sol:186","Staking.sol:192","Staking.sol:430","Staking.sol:443","Staking.sol:448"],"claim":"The checkpoint model collapses all same-epoch deposits into one `newDeposits` bucket with a single averaged `multiplier`, and `withdraw()` never tracks which tranche is actually being removed. If a user makes multiple deposits in the same epoch, withdrawing an earlier high-weight tranche only reduces `newDeposits` while preserving the averaged multiplier on the remainder. If a user starts the epoch with carried balance and then deposits late, withdrawing at least `newDeposits` moves the remainder into `startBalance` with `BASE_MULTIPLIER`, which can leave only the late deposit recorded as full-epoch stake.","impact":"A user can overstate their effective balance for the current epoch and capture more than their fair share of epoch rewards at the expense of honest stakers. Because this only requires timing deposits and withdrawals around the epoch boundary, it is a repeatable economic-extraction vector rather than a one-off accounting glitch.","paths":["Deposit a large amount early in an epoch, deposit a smaller amount near the epoch end, then withdraw the early deposit before rollover; the remaining late deposit keeps the blended multiplier instead of its true near-zero weight.","Begin the epoch with an existing carried balance, add a large deposit near the epoch end, then withdraw an amount equal to or larger than `newDeposits`; the code converts the remainder to `startBalance` with `BASE_MULTIPLIER`, so only the late deposit can remain while being credited as full-epoch stake."],"round":8,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-018","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Permissionless future epoch initialization can freeze stale pool sizes for later reward periods","locations":["Staking.sol:149","Staking.sol:394","Staking.sol:466","Staking.sol:479","Staking.sol:562"],"claim":"`manualEpochInit()` allows anyone to initialize arbitrary future epochs as long as the immediately previous epoch is initialized, and it copies the previous epoch's pool size verbatim. Later stake changes only refresh `poolSize[token][currentEpoch + 1]` inside `deposit()` and `withdraw()`. As a result, callers can pre-initialize epochs beyond `currentEpoch + 1`, and those farther-future snapshots will not be updated when balances subsequently change, even though `getEpochPoolSize()` will treat them as authoritative because `set == true`.","impact":"Attackers can lock in stale denominators for future reward epochs, causing later reward or accounting calculations to use obsolete pool sizes rather than the actual staked supply. This can overpay or underpay users and lets an attacker bias future epoch accounting without needing privileged access.","paths":["An epoch chain is initialized up to `N + 1` for some token.","Before more deposits or withdrawals occur, an attacker calls `manualEpochInit([token], N + 2)` or farther future epochs, copying the then-current size forward.","Honest users later change stake during epoch `N`, which updates only `poolSize[token][N + 1]` and leaves the pre-initialized `N + 2` snapshot stale.","When epoch `N + 2` is queried, `getEpochPoolSize(token, N + 2)` returns the stale initialized value instead of the real carried-forward pool size."],"round":9,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Contract referrers can bypass the EOA-only gate during construction","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"The constructor-time `extcodesize == 0` bypass is real in isolation, but this contract never uses referral state for payouts, permissions, or fund flows. On-chain impact is limited to metadata integrity, so the reported protocol harm is too speculative to keep as a reportable finding."},{"title":"Referral eligibility can be claimed retroactively after prior participation","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"`processReferrals()` only records referral relationships and counts; no reward-distribution or economic logic consumes that state anywhere in the codebase. Without a concrete on-chain value flow tied to referrals, this remains a low-value bookkeeping issue rather than realistic protocol-level harm."}]}
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/swapp_staking_1777179974/findings_acc.json:87:    "impact": "Attackers can create undercollateralized positions, farm rewards with less capital than recorded, and potentially withdraw honest users' later deposits of the same token. The pool's internal stake accounting can exceed the assets actually held by the contract.",
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/swapp_staking_1777179974/final_report.md:55:**Impact:** Attackers can create undercollateralized positions, farm rewards with less capital than recorded, and potentially withdraw honest users' later deposits of the same token. The pool's internal stake accounting can exceed the assets actually held by the contract.
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/onyxprotocol_p5_25_124/rounds/round_1/round_summary_stderr.log:62:    "impact": "A permissionless attacker can steal later deposits on thin or freshly seeded markets. After becoming the only shareholder and donating underlying directly to the market, the attacker can force a victim mint to round to zero and then redeem the victim's deposited assets together with the donation.",
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/onyxprotocol_p5_25_124/rounds/round_1/merge_stdout.log:1:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Direct underlying donations can inflate the exchange rate until later minters receive zero shares","locations":["0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:1625","0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:1638","0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:1783","0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:1814","0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:1821","0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:2909"],"claim":"The market prices shares from the raw underlying balance via `getCashPrior()`, so unsolicited token transfers raise the exchange rate without minting new oTokens. `mintFresh()` then computes `mintTokens = floor(actualMintAmount / exchangeRate)` and never rejects `mintTokens == 0`, allowing a seeded holder to donate enough underlying that a later depositor transfers assets in but receives no shares.","impact":"A permissionless attacker can steal later deposits on thin or freshly seeded markets. After becoming the only shareholder and donating underlying directly to the market, the attacker can force a victim mint to round to zero and then redeem the victim's deposited assets together with the donation.","paths":["Attacker mints a minimal amount to become the only oToken holder","Attacker transfers underlying directly to the oToken contract, increasing `getCashPrior()` without increasing `totalSupply`","Victim calls `mint()` and `mintTokens` truncates to 0","Attacker redeems their existing shares and withdraws both their donation and the victim's deposit"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"When total supply resets to zero, the next minter can capture stranded underlying at the initial exchange rate","locations":["0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:1625","0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:1627","0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:1632","0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:1783","0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:1821","0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:2909"],"claim":"`exchangeRateStoredInternal()` ignores the contract's actual underlying balance whenever `totalSupply == 0` and returns `initialExchangeRateMantissa` instead. If any underlying remains stranded in the market after all shares are redeemed, the first new minter buys in at the reset price and receives claims on both their own deposit and the pre-existing residual cash.","impact":"Residual underlying left behind by direct transfers, dust, or accounting edge cases can be swept by the first post-reset minter. This lets an attacker appropriate stranded value whenever a market's share supply is fully emptied.","paths":["All oTokens are redeemed so `totalSupply` becomes 0","Underlying remains in the contract due to direct transfers, dust, or other stranded balances","Attacker performs the first new mint at `initialExchangeRateMantissa`","Attacker redeems and captures the previously stranded underlying"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Liquidation treats any zero-decimal collateral market as NFT collateral","locations":["0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:2241","0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:2279","0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:2285","0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:2291","0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:2307"],"claim":"The liquidation path uses `oTokenCollateral.decimals() == 0` as the discriminator for NFT collateral. Token decimals are not a reliable asset-type check, so any listed fungible market with 0 decimals is forced into the NFT-specific `ComptrollerEx` repay-cap path instead of the normal fungible liquidation flow.","impact":"A zero-decimal ERC20 collateral market can become mis-liquidated or non-liquidatable, allowing unhealthy debt to persist and increasing the risk of bad debt or insolvency if such a market is listed.","paths":["A fungible underlying with 0 decimals is listed as collateral","A borrower opens a position against that market","A liquidator calls `liquidateBorrow()`","The call enters the NFT-specific branch solely because `decimals() == 0`, depending on incompatible liquidation logic"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"Any account can force-sweep arbitrary non-underlying tokens from a market to the admin","locations":["0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:2887","0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:2889","0x9dcb6bc351ab416f35aeab1351776e2ad295abc4/Contract.sol:2890","0x5fdbcd61bc9bd4b6d3fd1f49a5d253165ea11750/contracts/OErc20Delegator.sol:339","0x5fdbcd61bc9bd4b6d3fd1f49a5d253165ea11750/contracts/OErc20Delegator.sol:340"],"claim":"`sweepToken()` only checks that the token is not the market's underlying asset; it does not restrict the caller. Because the delegator exposes this method directly, any external account can trigger transfer of the entire balance of any other ERC20 held by the market to `admin`.","impact":"Third parties can front-run or grief token recovery by irreversibly redirecting accidentally sent or auxiliary tokens to the admin before the original owner or operators coordinate a rescue. This creates a permissionless loss-of-control vector around non-underlying assets held by the market.","paths":["A user or integration accidentally transfers a non-underlying ERC20 to the market","Any external account calls `sweepToken(token)`","The market transfers the entire token balance to `admin` without requiring admin authorization"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Liquidation for ERC721 Collateral Uses Inconsistent Calculations Leading to Undercollateralization","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The code repays `possibleRepayAmount` and then computes seized collateral from `actualRepayAmount`; that is internally consistent from the available code. The supported issue here is the `decimals()==0` type check, not a demonstrated under-seizure bug."},{"title":"Implementation Contract Not Validated Before Delegation","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is an admin-only upgradeability trust assumption inherent to the proxy pattern. No permissionless exploit or unexpected privilege bypass is shown."},{"title":"Missing Check for Zero Initial Exchange Rate","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The contract already requires `initialExchangeRateMantissa > 0`. Complaining about the absence of an upper bound is an admin-controlled deployment parameter, not a standalone protocol bug."},{"title":"Reserve Factor Can Be Set to 100%","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is an explicit governance-controlled parameter bounded by `reserveFactorMaxMantissa`; it is not a hidden vulnerability in the implementation."},{"title":"Division by Zero in exchangeRateStoredInternal if Total Supply is Zero","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`exchangeRateStoredInternal()` explicitly returns `initialExchangeRateMantissa` when `totalSupply == 0`, so the claimed division-by-zero path does not exist."},{"title":"Protocol Seize Share is Hardcoded Without Validation","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a design choice, not a security issue causing realistic protocol harm."},{"title":"No Maximum Borrow Rate Validation in Interest Rate Model","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`accrueInterest()` already reverts if `borrowRateMantissa > borrowRateMaxMantissa`. Installing a malicious model is an admin action, and the runtime check prevents silent over-accrual."},{"title":"ERC20 Transfer Handling May Fail Silently for Certain Tokens","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`doTransferOut()` inspects returndata and reverts on failure; it does not silently succeed when the token returns false or behaves non-compliantly."},{"title":"Delegatecall Risk in OErc20Delegator Allows Implementation to Modify Delegator Storage","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"That is the intended behavior of a delegatecall proxy and does not identify a concrete vulnerability beyond the normal trust model of upgradeable contracts."}]}
